-- Scottish House Prices Recover to 95 Percent of Peak, Lloyds Says
-- B y   T i m   F a r r a n d
-- 2012-08-17T10:10:32Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-08-17/scottish-house-prices-recover-to-95-percent-of-peak-lloyds-says.html
Scottish  house prices  rose 7.3
percent in the three months to July 31, with the number of
transactions also increasing, Lloyds TSB Scotland reported.  The average price is now 164,122 pounds ($257,900), equal
to 95 percent of their peak four years ago, the bank said in its
 Scottish House Price Monitor .  The largest pickup in the market was at the higher-value
end with the number of transactions for detached properties in
the Monitor increasing by 47 percent compared with the same
period a year earlier, it said in an e-mailed statement today.  Average prices increased 0.6 percent in Dundee in the 12
months to July and by 1 percent in Glasgow,  Scotland â€™s biggest
city. Aberdeen had the largest decline, with prices losing 9.9
percent, while in the capital, Edinburgh, they fell 7.1 percent,
according to the Monitor.  To contact the reporter on this story:
